Wei Wuhou deliberated on matters and was always correct, and none of his ministers could match his insight. After court, he wore a look of joy. Wu Qi stepped forward and said, “Has anyone ever shared King Zhuang of Chu’s words with you, my lord?”  

Wei Wuhou asked, “What were King Zhuang of Chu’s words?”  

Wu Qi replied, “King Zhuang of Chu once deliberated on matters and was correct, with none of his ministers able to equal him—yet after court, he wore a worried look. Shen Gong Wu Chen approached and asked, ‘My king, why do you look worried after court?’ King Zhuang said, ‘I deliberate and am correct, but none of my ministers can match me—that is why I worry. There is a saying in the *Zhongrui* (an ancient text) that goes: “Among feudal lords, those who have a teacher to guide them will achieve kingship; those who have a friend to advise them will attain hegemony; those who have someone to question them will survive; but those who plan solely for themselves and deem no one equal to them will perish.” Now, with my own lack of virtue, yet none of my ministers can match me—my country is perilously close to collapse! That is why I worry.’ King Zhuang of Chu worried over this, but you take joy in it.”  

Wei Wuhou hesitated, then bowed twice and said, “Heaven has sent you, sir, to correct my mistake.”  


### (2) Moral of the Story  

The core moral is that a leader’s isolation from constructive criticism and diverse perspectives is a recipe for downfall. Wei Wuhou’s joy stems from believing he is incomparably wise, but this arrogance blinds him to the danger of having no one to challenge his decisions. In contrast, Chu Zhuangwang’s worry reflects wisdom: true leadership requires surrounding oneself with teachers (who guide), friends (who advise openly), and even doubters (who question assumptions). Without such input, a leader becomes detached from reality, and their “correctness” becomes a hollow boast—ultimately leading to the state’s decline. The story emphasizes that humility and openness to feedback are far more critical to governance than individual brilliance.  


